I lead customer marketing at Posit. I've learned from a friend at the Hangout that it might

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:28.240
be helpful for me to let people know that Posit is actually the company formerly called

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:36.080
RStudio. I had assumed that mistakenly, that everybody knew that. So I just want to make

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:41.919
sure that I add that in the beginning as well. So at Posit, we build enterprise solutions

00:00:41.919 --> 00:00:48.959
and open source tools for people who do data science with both R and Python. And so I'm

00:00:48.959 --> 00:00:53.279
joined by my lovely co-host here as well, Libby, if you want to introduce yourself.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:00.400
Hi, I'm Libby. I work with Posit to do community management for the Data Science Hangout, and I'm

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:06.959
also a data science mentor at the Posit Academy, where I help people learn R and Python to do their

00:01:06.959 --> 00:01:13.680
jobs better. So happy to have you all joining us here today. If this is your first Data Science

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:19.839
Hangout, this is our open space to hear what's going on in the world of data across all different

00:01:19.839 --> 00:01:25.440
industries, chat about data science leadership, and connect with others who are facing similar

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:32.559
things as you. And we get together here every Thursday at the same time, same place. So if you

00:01:32.559 --> 00:01:38.239
are watching us as a recording on YouTube and want to join us live in the future, there'll

00:01:38.239 --> 00:01:45.360
be details to add it to your own calendar below. At the Hangout, we're all dedicated to keeping this

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:51.120
a friendly and welcoming space for everyone, and love hearing from you no matter your years of

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:57.760
experience, titles, industry, or languages that you work in. And I know people really enjoy connecting

00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:03.279
with other attendees here in the chat, so I'll encourage you if you want to right now to briefly

00:02:03.279 --> 00:02:08.720
introduce yourself and say hi, maybe share your LinkedIn or include your role, something you do

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:16.160
for fun. That chat is yours to use during the Hangout to connect with other people.

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:20.399
Feel free to also share any open roles that your team may be hiring for too.

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:26.399
Yes, please share open roles, share your website, whatever you can.

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:32.000
There are three ways that you can jump in and ask questions today, or just share your own experience

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:37.679
or point of view. You can raise your hand on Zoom and we will call on you to jump in. You can put a

00:02:37.679 --> 00:02:43.279
question in the Zoom chat. Feel free to put an asterisk next to it, after it, before it. If you

00:02:43.279 --> 00:02:47.039
are someplace noisy or your mic doesn't work, you're not able to read it yourself, we'll read

00:02:47.039 --> 00:02:53.839
it for you. And then we also have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously, and that

00:02:53.839 --> 00:03:00.320
will be in the chat. I think Isabella has already posted it in the chat. Yeah, there we go. Awesome.

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:05.119
Well, I'm so excited to be joined today by our co-host Ralph Asher, who is the founder of Data

00:03:05.119 --> 00:03:10.720
Driven Supply Chain LLC. Hey, Ralph, I would love to get started with you just telling us a little

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:17.759
bit about yourself, how you maybe got into data and supply chain. And I would also love to hear

00:03:17.759 --> 00:03:22.880
a little bit about what you do outside of work. Great. Well, thank you, first off, Libby and

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:27.199
Rachel, for inviting me. This is a great opportunity to connect with the data community and just talk

00:03:27.199 --> 00:03:32.320
a little bit about the supply chain design and the associated disciplines. So, background,

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:38.320
grew up in Indiana, in small town Indiana, went to hometown U, as I call it, studied physics,

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:42.479
and about halfway through, I realized I wasn't that great at physics, so I joined the Marines

00:03:42.479 --> 00:03:48.880
after graduation. That's half a joke, but I love the ability to understand how real life is

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:56.800
connected to math, and so studied physics and wanted to serve my country. For six years after

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:03.520
college, I was on active duty in the Marine Corps as a communications officer where I led

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:08.479
teams of technical Marines who were doing things like setting up radio networks and computer

00:04:08.479 --> 00:04:14.800
networks and things like that. Towards the end of that time, went back to school for operations

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:19.119
research, which for those who might be an unfamiliar term, operations research is the

00:04:19.119 --> 00:04:26.720
discipline of essentially problem solving using math with different disciplines of mathematics,

00:04:26.720 --> 00:04:31.600
optimization, statistics, and engineering, all mixed together towards solving problems. So,

00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:35.600
went back to school, got my master's in that, moved to Minnesota and started working at

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:40.399
General Mills, the food company, which is here, doing supply chain design. And what supply chain

00:04:40.399 --> 00:04:47.119
design is, is basically using those operations research techniques to inform where a company

00:04:47.119 --> 00:04:51.200
or an organization should have their manufacturing plants, where they should have their distribution

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:56.160
centers, their warehouses, how products should ultimately flow to their customers. So, worked

00:04:56.160 --> 00:05:01.440
there for a couple years, then was hired to work at Target, which is located here also in Minnesota,

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:06.480
and worked there for several years before starting my company doing consulting on supply chain

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:13.200
design and inventory optimization and some related things. Outside of work, I like to run, I like to

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:19.119
be active. Minnesota is great for that. I also have two small children and a minivan and a dog

00:05:19.119 --> 00:05:25.920
and a house, so kind of got all my hands full as far as that goes. Awesome, Ralph, thank you. I was

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:31.519
hoping, yeah, as Rachel's saying, I see some Target friends on here too. I think we've had

00:05:31.519 --> 00:05:37.600
Target supply chain friends join us in the past as well. I would love to hear a little bit about,

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:42.640
for anybody who isn't aware of the type of problems that are solved in supply chain,

00:05:42.640 --> 00:05:47.679
would you mind giving us a little rundown or some background on the types of problems that

00:05:47.679 --> 00:05:53.040
you solve, maybe for a place like Target, and what type of data you use to solve your problems?

00:05:53.760 --> 00:06:01.359
Sure. So, types of problems, one is what I alluded to earlier, so facility location.

00:06:01.359 --> 00:06:05.760
Where should my distribution centers be? Where should my plants be? I'm also going to use some

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:11.279
examples from when I was at General Mills. How big should they be? How much capacity, meaning how much

00:06:11.279 --> 00:06:14.959
storage and how much throughput, how fast can they get product out the door? How much should

00:06:14.959 --> 00:06:20.559
that do? If you're talking about a manufacturer or even with a distribution center, what types of

00:06:20.559 --> 00:06:27.119
products should be put in those facilities? So, for example, if you go into a Target, you can see

00:06:27.119 --> 00:06:32.720
that there's things like clothing and electronics that can go through just a standard ambient

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:36.239
temperature warehouse that doesn't really have temperature control, but you also have things like

00:06:36.239 --> 00:06:39.920
milk and eggs and cheese, and that has to go through a refrigerated warehouse, and then you

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:45.279
have things like frozen pizza, frozen vegetables, that has to go through a frozen warehouse. And so,

00:06:45.279 --> 00:06:50.079
those are actually separate supply chains, and you need to design your network in accordance with

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:56.399
the demands for those temperature channels and where your demand is geographically.

00:06:56.399 --> 00:07:01.839
Some other questions are around inventory. So, for example, how much of a product should I stock

00:07:01.839 --> 00:07:08.640
in my store or in my warehouse to both satisfy my customer demand but not also hold too much

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:13.679
inventory? Because inventory ultimately is money tied up in physical form, and so you want to have

00:07:13.679 --> 00:07:18.720
a trade-off between having enough to satisfy your customer's demands but not having too much where

00:07:18.720 --> 00:07:23.839
you're unnecessarily tying up money in that sense. For the last several years I worked at Target,

00:07:24.399 --> 00:07:29.440
I was working on what's called last-mile network design. So, inside the e-commerce realm,

00:07:30.399 --> 00:07:35.519
how do we design e-commerce networks to ensure fast delivery to the customers,

00:07:35.679 --> 00:07:40.559
calls, and guests of their e-commerce packages in a way that is both highly convenient to that

00:07:40.559 --> 00:07:45.679
customer but also cost-effective and makes sense from the business side of it? So, those are some

00:07:45.679 --> 00:07:51.519
of the big things in supply chain design and supply chain optimization, but it goes way past that one.

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:58.320
It does, I'm sure. I wanted you to talk a little bit about it because I think that supply chain is

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:05.040
a super data-driven field that kind of gets ignored by people when they're looking to move

00:08:05.119 --> 00:08:10.880
into data. And you didn't start in data, right? You moved into supply chain. So,

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:18.480
I was wondering if you could talk a little bit about the sort of market or maybe advice that

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:23.279
you've seen for people who are shifting into data and what they might be able to do because there's

00:08:23.279 --> 00:08:28.559
a lot of data jobs that we see that are like, we think of prediction only, or we think of

00:08:28.559 --> 00:08:33.200
inferential statistics only. And supply chain is a little bit different in that it's optimization,

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:37.840
right? Yeah. Well, the nice thing about supply chain, and this will touch a little bit on your

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:43.200
data question, is that depending upon what you're interested in, both from an analytical perspective

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:48.960
and from just a career trajectory perspective, supply chain offers a lot of opportunities. So,

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:54.400
if you are in the data visualization space, there's a great market for people who want to focus on

00:08:54.400 --> 00:09:00.159
BI diagnostic analytics within supply chain. If you're more in the forecasting and the predictive

00:09:00.159 --> 00:09:04.320
space, that's a huge market, right? Because we need to predict how much demand the product is

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:10.000
going to be. We need to predict how much activity we're going to have in our warehouses or our plants

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:14.159
so we know how to staff appropriately. Now, if you go into more of the prescriptive things,

00:09:14.159 --> 00:09:18.239
like operations research and optimization, there's plenty of work there and some of the

00:09:18.239 --> 00:09:22.559
things I spoke to before. So, one of the awesome things about supply chain as a data field

00:09:23.359 --> 00:09:28.000
is that there's something for everybody. And if you're more on the data engineering side too,

00:09:28.960 --> 00:09:33.599
supply chains run on data. Supply chains generate data left, right, and center. Whether or not the

00:09:33.599 --> 00:09:38.239
organizations are aware of that or using it, it's there. And so, there's opportunity there,

00:09:38.239 --> 00:09:42.960
and it's an awesome field if you are somebody that is both interested in the analytical technical

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:47.440
side but also interested in solving real-world problems that actually matter to people. And

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:52.159
that's something that was a real draw to me initially and continues to be a draw for me.

00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:57.200
I agree. I feel like everyone is affected by the supply chain. No matter who they are,

00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:00.159
you can't escape it, and it's a way to touch a lot of lives.

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:06.239
I see a great question, George, in the chat. Would you like to ask that?

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:14.960
Sure. Yeah, thanks. So, can you hear me okay, by the way? I'm trying out a new microphone.

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:16.320
Yeah, you're all right.

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:25.359
Yeah, I was curious about how COVID-19 may have impacted what you do, especially because,

00:10:26.320 --> 00:10:31.760
and I think a lot of fields are going through this, where all of our kind of OHUM stats,

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:38.719
you know, like our dashboards and everything, which had variation in it, just kind of went

00:10:38.719 --> 00:10:49.599
really crazy. I'm in HR, and we had just crazy, like, turnover. And so, I'm just kind of wondering,

00:10:49.760 --> 00:10:56.880
did you anticipate any of that? And how did you adjust to the changes that we saw with COVID-19?

00:10:59.599 --> 00:11:03.280
That's a great question. I think that I'll answer the second part first. I think that,

00:11:04.239 --> 00:11:11.520
of course, COVID-19, and not so much the disease itself and the epidemic itself, but rather the

00:11:12.479 --> 00:11:17.599
actions associated with preventing it. So, things like, you know, social distancing,

00:11:17.599 --> 00:11:21.679
that means that if you're working in a manufacturing plant, you're usually working

00:11:21.679 --> 00:11:27.119
pretty close to each other. Right now, you can't, which means you're working more slowly. Or things

00:11:27.119 --> 00:11:33.359
like we saw with the port backups, because of a whole lot more ships coming from East Asia into

00:11:34.719 --> 00:11:38.880
the Southern California ports, Los Angeles and Long Beach. So, a lot of these things we saw

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:47.280
during COVID-19, I think, are somewhat unique in the sense that we had a intersection point of

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:53.520
multiple major disruptions to global supply chains from both a supply side and a demand side.

00:11:54.080 --> 00:12:00.080
And that is probably not going to happen to that level of magnitude in my lifetime again. At least

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:07.119
I hope not. And so, the question then is, you know, what are the lessons we should learn from

00:12:07.119 --> 00:12:14.320
it going forward? I think there's a lot of discussions, and I've been in them, around

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:21.200
when we look at, say, 2020 through 2022 from a demand perspective, do you just take the actuals,

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:25.280
or do you smooth that out and do some sort of interpolation? Because you don't want to

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:31.599
necessarily just use the history as a prediction of what's going forward. More broadly, there's a

00:12:31.599 --> 00:12:35.679
lot of discussions around supply chain leaders around, you know, what do we do with our supply

00:12:35.679 --> 00:12:41.520
chains going forward? There's, you know, you can read the news about geopolitical tensions and the

00:12:41.520 --> 00:12:45.760
impacts to specifically things like critical supply chains around semiconductors. There's a

00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:54.400
lot of news coming out of the White House around that. And so, there's a lot of discussions about

00:12:54.400 --> 00:12:59.200
how to handle these things. I don't think anybody has the right answer. And frankly, the right answer

00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:03.520
for you and your company is going to be different than even another company in your same industry,

00:13:03.520 --> 00:13:11.760
much less a different industry. Thank you. Big, huge answer to maybe an unanswerable question.

00:13:12.479 --> 00:13:19.359
Ralph, I have a question about your decision to strike out on your own, because I feel like

00:13:19.359 --> 00:13:24.080
there are a lot of people right now, including me in the past couple of years, who have thought

00:13:24.719 --> 00:13:30.159
maybe I could freelance, maybe I could do consulting. So, I'm wondering what your decision

00:13:30.159 --> 00:13:37.440
process was like? How did you know it was time to go out on your own? Yeah, great. So, I really enjoy

00:13:37.440 --> 00:13:42.479
the problem-solving component of this type of work, and that was what I really liked about my

00:13:42.479 --> 00:13:47.440
corporate job. And I was talking with a friend of mine. I said, hey, I really enjoy this, but I'm

00:13:47.440 --> 00:13:51.440
kind of doing less of it as time goes on. He said, well, have you thought about consulting? This was

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:57.679
pre-COVID. And at that point, most consulting firms were traveling, you know, four days a week and

00:13:57.760 --> 00:14:01.599
young family not really interested in that. Then when COVID struck, you know, everybody's

00:14:02.640 --> 00:14:07.119
working from home for the most part. I thought, you know, this seems like a real great time to

00:14:07.119 --> 00:14:12.479
kind of strike out and start my own company. And, you know, if things don't work out, I can

00:14:12.479 --> 00:14:20.719
go back to work at a quote-unquote real job eventually. So, in terms of what I did and what

00:14:20.719 --> 00:14:27.200
I would give as advice, don't do it on a lark. Don't just wake up and say, man, I don't like my job.

00:14:27.679 --> 00:14:31.599
I'm done with this. And go from there. You need to do a lot of preparation. So,

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:37.760
one of the things that people tend to not necessarily realize when they're working in

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:42.640
a real job is like how much of a support structure is associated with that job you have. So,

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:48.400
they're paying your half of your taxes. Like they are, at least on the Medicare and the

00:14:48.400 --> 00:14:52.400
Social Security side, they're providing your health insurance maybe in your retirement plan.

00:14:53.119 --> 00:14:57.440
If you're on your own, like you're on your own. That's all yours. And so, you got to think about

00:14:57.679 --> 00:15:02.960
how are you going to have a business entity? Are you going to find clients? What kind of work are

00:15:02.960 --> 00:15:09.359
you going to do? And then how are you going to address things like, you know, health insurance

00:15:09.359 --> 00:15:13.200
and all those other things that, for the most part, are just kind of given to you when you

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:18.640
start a job. And I can go into detail on any of those, but broadly, that's kind of what I would

00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:28.479
say. Thank you. I will leave people in the chat to ask nosy questions. I saw a question in Slido,

00:15:28.479 --> 00:15:34.080
which was, with the increasing amount of data available, how do you make sure that insights

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:39.039
derived are actionable and are not overwhelmed by noise or irrelevant information?

00:15:39.200 --> 00:15:47.359
Oh, that is a great one. I think that, yeah, as data becomes more and more available, it does

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.760
give us the temptation to think that I can just get a little bit more detail,

00:15:52.559 --> 00:15:55.119
or I just need a little bit more and I can make a little bit better decision.

00:15:55.919 --> 00:16:02.960
I think something that is a characteristic that was imbued to me in the military and then really

00:16:03.919 --> 00:16:09.280
kind of crystallized by my teaching operations research is to understand what are the prime

00:16:09.280 --> 00:16:14.559
movers? Like, what are the biggest things that matter the most? And what are the things that,

00:16:14.559 --> 00:16:19.039
if they are different, would change your decision? And if they aren't different,

00:16:19.039 --> 00:16:25.520
would change your decision? And so it's helpful to just say, if this thing we're tracking,

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:31.679
if it was higher or lower, would we make a different decision? And if so, how big of a

00:16:31.760 --> 00:16:35.039
magnitude would that decision be differently? Because if it's not going to be that big of a

00:16:35.039 --> 00:16:40.960
difference, then it's not going to change what you would be doing. And if it's not going to

00:16:40.960 --> 00:16:46.320
change what you'd be doing, you don't need to pay that close of attention to it. I think that's the

00:16:46.320 --> 00:16:53.359
biggest thing. And that's going to be, of course, context dependent. What that means for a retail

00:16:53.359 --> 00:16:57.679
supply chain is going to be different from a consumer packaged goods supply chain, which is

00:16:57.679 --> 00:17:05.119
going to be different from any other sector. Yeah, man, some of these questions, I feel like

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:12.239
I, full disclosure, I did supply chain in my undergrad. So I'm fascinated by the stuff that

00:17:12.239 --> 00:17:16.959
Ralph is working on, but my head is kind of spinning on what I could have done if I had

00:17:16.959 --> 00:17:21.199
gone into supply chain full time. There are so many unique questions to answer.

00:17:21.760 --> 00:17:26.800
I see a question in the chat from Jonathan. Would you like to unmute and answer that or ask that

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:33.839
one? Yeah, thanks. Are you able to hear me okay? Yes. Excellent. So my question to you is, given the

00:17:33.839 --> 00:17:38.079
exponential age of data, do you see any fundamental issues with data management and governance in your

00:17:38.079 --> 00:17:45.920
line of work? And if so, could you give any concrete examples of that? Oh, yeah. I mean,

00:17:45.920 --> 00:17:51.520
that's definitely an issue. I mean, any supply chain, you have to have a real emphasis upon

00:17:51.520 --> 00:17:58.160
data management, data governance, even though it's not always the most flashy of disciplines,

00:17:58.160 --> 00:18:03.680
for sure. That was never really my space. I mean, I worked with the people who worked in that space,

00:18:03.680 --> 00:18:08.000
but it was never something I was particularly close to in terms of the day-to-day. So

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:14.079
unfortunately, I can't give too many examples about that. That's all right. Totally valid answer.

00:18:15.359 --> 00:18:19.920
I have a question. I've heard you talk before about marketing yourself, and you talked a little

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:25.599
bit about how do you find people when you're striking out on your own. Can you talk a little

00:18:25.599 --> 00:18:31.040
bit about what advice you would give job seekers around marketing themselves, whether they're new

00:18:31.040 --> 00:18:39.520
grads or switching industries? Yeah, that's great. So if you're looking to switch industry, new grad,

00:18:40.479 --> 00:18:45.680
I would say the biggest thing is find a tagline and lean into it. So what do I mean by a tagline?

00:18:45.680 --> 00:18:50.719
I'm going to say something completely unrelated to supply chain. Say, hi, my name is John Smith,

00:18:50.719 --> 00:18:56.160
and I'm looking for a position in marketing analytics in the greater Denver area. Okay,

00:18:56.160 --> 00:19:03.359
that's a tagline. What does that do? That now gives somebody three things, three hooks that

00:19:03.359 --> 00:19:09.680
they can get in, that they can help you. Now, maybe, or either help you or refer to others.

00:19:09.680 --> 00:19:14.239
So somebody says, hey, I'm looking for marketing analytics positions in Denver.

00:19:14.959 --> 00:19:19.280
Well, I know somebody in marketing. Most people know somebody in marketing. I'm going to introduce

00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:24.400
you to that person in marketing. Or, oh, Denver, my cousin lives there. Maybe he knows somebody

00:19:24.400 --> 00:19:29.439
that's in the more marketing space locally. It gives you something that allows you, maybe not

00:19:29.439 --> 00:19:33.599
that first person that you talk to is probably not going to be the one saying, wow, I have been

00:19:33.599 --> 00:19:38.479
looking for you my whole life. Here's a job. What they're going to do is they're going to give you

00:19:39.280 --> 00:19:44.719
those second, third, fourth connections. And you need to give those people something to help you

00:19:44.719 --> 00:19:53.359
with. What doesn't help is saying, hi, I'm willing to do any job. Like, I don't know how to help you.

00:19:54.560 --> 00:20:02.880
And so find that tagline, lean into it. And then something that I read early on in my career,

00:20:02.880 --> 00:20:08.719
and I think this is very helpful, is to say that if you want to have an extraordinary career,

00:20:09.599 --> 00:20:13.119
there's two ways to do it. One is to be the absolute best in the world at something,

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:20.239
which vast majority of us are not going to be. It doesn't matter how much you like singing or

00:20:20.239 --> 00:20:25.599
playing basketball. You're probably not going to be LeBron James or Taylor Swift. There's not that

00:20:25.599 --> 00:20:33.520
many people at the tippy-tippy top of any field. But pick two or three things that are independently

00:20:33.520 --> 00:20:39.599
valuable. Aim to be in the top quartile of each of those. And now suddenly you have that unique

00:20:41.040 --> 00:20:47.439
skill set. So I mean, it's honestly not that hard to be in the top 25% of anything. I would guess

00:20:47.439 --> 00:20:52.079
that by being on this call, everybody here is in the top 25% of data analytics across the entire

00:20:52.079 --> 00:20:57.520
population, probably significantly higher for most of you. So now commit yourself to learning

00:20:57.520 --> 00:21:01.839
supply chain or marketing or finance or whatever it is and get better at that. So now you have that

00:21:01.839 --> 00:21:06.000
intersection point. That's something that I would highly recommend. And it goes kind of that

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:14.000
tagline as well. I so totally agree with this. I just want to like add my agreement to it because

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:20.160
when I first started freelancing, I either didn't get work or didn't get the right work for a long

00:21:20.160 --> 00:21:26.959
time. And I was telling people I can do anything in XYZ. And until I started telling people here is

00:21:26.959 --> 00:21:32.479
exactly what I do and what I want to do, I just wasn't getting any traction. But once I started

00:21:32.479 --> 00:21:36.000
putting that out there, everybody that I talked to, I said, hey, this exactly is what I want to do.

00:21:36.719 --> 00:21:43.439
The opportunities started popping up way, way, way more. And I also kind of almost want to call out

00:21:43.439 --> 00:21:50.560
Mark, who's on this call right now, Mark Rieke, because Mark, I know you were on my podcast with

00:21:50.560 --> 00:21:56.560
me and you said that you were at the gym with a friend and you told him what you wanted to do.

